In [16]:
def find_cycle(sequences, low, high):
    '''
    Find the cycle in which these sequences are distinguishable.
    This point should be < 140.
    '''
 
    mid = (high + low) // 2
    
    nunique = sequences.str.slice(0, mid).nunique()
    
    if low >= high:
        return mid

    elif nunique < len(sequences):
        return find_cycle(sequences, mid + 1, high)

    # Else the element can only be present in right subarray
    elif nunique == len(sequences):
        return find_cycle(sequences, low, mid - 1)
    else:
        raise
    
cycle = find_cycle(annot_df["sequence"], 0, len(annot_df["sequence"].iloc[0]))
print("Sequences are distinguishable at %i bp" % cycle)
verify(cycle < 140)

GC content and thermodynamics¶

  • GC content should be between 0.3 and 0.7 for most sequences
  • Tm: uses seqfold library to compute the annealing temperature between seq1 and its reverse complement. Higher temperature usually means higher stability, which may cause problems during PCR.
  • dG: uses RNAfold to compute the minimum free energy of a sequence. lower numbers indicate higher stability, which may cause issues.

Some references:¶

  • For both Inness and Santigold, dG and Tm centers around -11 and 80, respectively

def compute_kmer_stats(kmer_data):
    """
    "coverage" counts the number of times the k-mer is observed across the whole dataset, while
    "multiplicity" counts the number of sequences that contain each k-mer.
    """
    k = kmer_data["k"]
    kmer_coverage = np.asarray(list(kmer_data["kmer_coverage"].values()))
    kmer_multiplicity = np.asarray(list(kmer_data["kmer_multiplicity"].values()))
    
    stats = {"k": k, "total_kmers": total_kmers(k)}
    stats["num_obs_kmers"] = len(kmer_coverage)
    stats["frac_kmers_observed"] = len(kmer_coverage) / total_kmers(k)
    stats["num_coverage1_kmers"] = (kmer_coverage == 1).sum()
    stats["num_multiplicity1_kmers"] = (kmer_multiplicity == 1).sum()
    stats["avg_kmer_coverage"] = np.mean(kmer_coverage)
    stats["avg_kmer_multiplicity"] = np.mean(kmer_multiplicity)
    stats["max_kmer_coverage"] = np.max(kmer_coverage)
    stats["max_kmer_multiplicity"] = np.max(kmer_multiplicity)
    stats["median_kmer_coverage"] = np.median(kmer_coverage)
    stats["median_kmer_multiplicity"] = np.median(kmer_multiplicity)
    
    return stats

Global k-mer stats¶

  • coverage: number of times a kmer is observed
  • multiplicity: number of sequences a kmer is observed in

Here, we collect kmer stats for multiple values of k:

  • total_kmers: number of possible kmers for this value of k
  • num_obs_kmers: number of observed kmers
  • frac_kmers_observed: fraction of kmers observed
  • num_coverage1_kmers: number of kmers found just once
  • num_multiplicity1_kmers: number of kmers found in just one sequences
  • max/median/avg_kmer_coverage: max/median/average coverage across each kmer
  • max/median/avg_kmer_multiplicity: max/median/average multiplicity across each kmer

Note: the k-mer matrix is switched from LIL format to CSR format.
